segments.text: This is March 30, 1988.
We're in the class of planning 654.
Our guest today is Mr. Leon Wilhite, a graduate of the Department of Urban and Regional Planning in May of 1971.
Leon was one of our first graduates and has had one job since he left the department.
He's been in the governor's office in Austin ever since.
and has lived through five different governor terms, one of which has been repeated.
And I want to familiarize the class a little bit with state planning and the possibilities that abound at state level for many of our graduates and the need for good planners at the state level.
Leon?
It's a pleasure to have you here today, as always, and we're looking forward to what you can tell us about your longevity in Austin.
Good.

I would like to make this as informal as we can, and I know some of you, one person needs to leave at 3.30, and if you get really tired of this, you can raise your hand, and I'll let you go, if that's all right.
Bob was always a tough taskmaster in school.
He was always...
But I think we ought to just consider this an informal discussion.
And if you have questions or you'd like to make comments about Bob, we'll just go ahead and say it.
He was always a fun professor to be around because he tells you exactly the way he feels.
I think he encourages other students to do the same thing.
We did.
We told him.
Didn't we?
I do remember.
OK.
I handed out a little outline of discussion.
I'd like to whip through this fairly quickly.
Give us a little time to discuss what you're interested in talking about.
Starting back, let me tell you a couple of things about myself.
I started working in the governor's office in 1971.
Back then, we had a division called the Division of Planning Coordination.
When I joined that staff, it was known pretty much around the country as being a policy planning staff, a fairly progressive policy planning staff.
Bob, of course, dealing with California and other parts of the country, was much more familiar with the traditional planning.
Come in.
Here's a seat just for you.
But the division planning coordination in the governor's office was a policy planning office, and we won national awards during that period of time and was fairly nationally known.
I was really pleased to join that staff and was excited over the couple of years there, the first couple of years out of school.
It was a dynamic office.
I guess the average age was around 26 to 28.
The director was 32.
And so it was a real fun time.
It was a dynamic time, a real challenge for us all.
I'll talk a little bit more about the governors and the styles.
But let's talk quickly about planning the legislation.
Life didn't begin in 65, but it seemed like in any kind of planning responsibility, they really didn't use much terms in state government before about 1965.
And we had a law passed in 65 that created the ability for local governments to form regional planning commissions.
And that's in Article 1011M.
Most of you have access to Vernon's here at the school if you have any interest in looking up these laws, you're welcome to.
Let me just say also, early 70s, we compiled a book.
It's really, they're out of print right now, but this was the legal basis for planning in Texas.
And I mean, this is a real, it breaks it down functionally in education, general government, natural resource.
It's a
very extensive document, and anything that relates at all to the planning, they have it listed in here.
So it's something, I don't know, Bob, if you've ever seen this or not, have you?
I never have.
We've been keeping it secret from Bob.
I was wondering if there's any one body of planning law in Texas.
Not other than what's in here.
There's no real body of single place.
This is scattered throughout the state hall.
But if you
have interest or want to research that.
I wouldn't be surprised if your library didn't have this.
I can work through Bob if anyone really thinks that's interesting.
I'll share that with you.
But anyway, in 1967 was the first year that we appropriated law for regional planning.
We created regional councils beginning back in 65, 66.
We appropriated $250,000 for the 24 regional councils.
We also, in 1967, created a law that said that the governor was chief planning officer of the state.
Those are broad general comments.
The law was about a one-page law.
It said the governor could create interagency planning councils, which meant that they were agency heads.
state government agency heads, the governor could form these councils to work on issues.
We had back in the, I guess the primary time that I recall, we had about five or six that were functionally broken down like natural resources, human services, and so forth.
But this is as close to a cabinet form of government that we have.
It's where the governor can form a council with agency heads
to work on issues and problems.
It was, I think, a breakthrough in Texas because, again, we just hadn't had any state-level planning laws.
And it was an approach where the governor could actually call these guys together and work on issues.
I wanted to bring out to you that I don't know if it's typical or not, but in my experience, I think it's fairly typical.
The federal government
tends to make states do what they ought to do.
You know, being a states' rights kind of a guy that I am, I have to really choke on those words.
But many times we find that the federal government makes us do things that we should do.
Planning is one of those areas.
701 planning, in fact, was the primary reason that we created a planning shop in the governor's office.
It provided a basic
planning pot of money to hire planners.
And of course, that's waned.
I think the last year that states got 701 planning money was about 78 or 79.
But just on your list, we also had quite a bit of planning funds in the transportation area.
The Department of Transportation funded fairly substantial
planning shops in both the state level as well as regional and local levels.

Then the old HEW, Health Education Welfare, back in the, I guess through about maybe mid-70s, was a major federal agency that funded everything from health planning to family planning to different kinds of issues.
I really think any time you're looking at state-level planning in Texas or any other state, you've got to recognize that the federal government played a fairly major role.
What I'd like to do is walk through the governor's role in all of this.
And I will throw in a few words, I guess, of really how good these guys were.
I'm a little bit uncomfortable with Bob's Rick Carter here, but I'll throw some in, and then we can cut it off, and I can tell you really what I think.
John Conley was, of course, a Democrat in those days, was a strong governor, had a lot of charisma, a lot of energy.
He had a governor's staff in those early days of, you know, I think he had one
to maybe five max program type staff.
We have probably 150 now, just to give you a feel.
And we're small now compared to what we used to be.
But Connolly had, I mean, there just wasn't much in the governor's office.
They had a scheduler, and they had a few people like what we'd call personal staff, but nothing in the program area.
Back in those days, Terrell Blodgett was the governor's executive assistant, and he was
kind of a program staffer.
He was really more of a personal aide.
A guy named Jim Ray, who's still around Texas, was the first planning director in the governor's office, and he was under John Connolly.
Back at that day, they were just beginning to do planning.
They were, in fact, the first planning grant that they got under Connolly in terms of federal planning money was the health plan.
They were able to get a grant.
It's funny that we
that the first planning grant that we get in the state was health planning, which has always been kind of a side issue.
But it was at least a couple of years during the health planning funding days that we finally got the 701 plan.
But under Connolly, I consider those days the beginning years.
The laws were passed relative to regional planning and state
chief planning officer, governor laws.
But there was a very small staff.
They began at that time creating regional planning councils, as I mentioned earlier.

When I say the governor's staff, they'd literally go out and meet with city and county governments, and they'd start explaining to them how they could form a regional planning body, what the body ought to do.
And they did
what I call missionary work in the planning, trying to get some of the stuff done.
This was done by a very small staff.
As Jim Ray continued, he probably had no more than five planners on board at that point.
About that time, Preston Smith came into office, 1969.
Preston, to me, was one of the better governors.

And let me define a better governor, I guess a better governor to me is a chief type leader that can select top staff that gives them their head and allows them to be innovative, creative, that will listen to the staff, you know, a lot, you know, obviously, the decision makers going to make the decisions.
But as a

The planning director ought to feel very comfortable with recommending anything to the governor, giving him the pros and the cons to the political action or political ramifications, as well as the positives and negatives.
To me, the Preston Smith days, I think, were almost the Camelot years in planning.
Dan Petty was the director during most of that time.
And Ed Grisham was a guy that finished up the last couple of years.
And this was the years.
And I wanted to point out that we had, I guess, Goldsboro, Texas probably was one of the primary reasons, Bob, that our little shop got national acclaim.
Goldsboro, Texas really put the state planning office in Texas on the map.
We had two phases, phase one, phase two.
Then we had phase three.
That was the budget that, at that time, we were still struggling over how you deal with planning and how you deal with financing planning.
And we've still been struggling over that ever since.
But at that time, they said, you know, really, if you do proper planning, it ought to play into the budget.
And the budget and the planning ought to be kind of together.
Well, this year, we produced a program-type budget where the goals for Texas
and the budget document were actually kind of merged, where we do have in the budget.
Let me skip that.
We do have a budget to where they actually break it down functionally.
Most of the state budgets have always been agency by agency.
And this is the first where they broke it down
functionally, like education, general government, health, human resources, natural resources.
And it was the primary, like, ten functions.
You start talking about planning, ten, I don't know if ten's a good round number or not, but that's kind of the, if you'll break it down any time, you'll come up with a round ten.
This was a good piece of work, and a work that
I think really did put us on the map.
It actually got into talking about what an objective was, what a goal was.
Not only two year, five year, 10 year goals, but it had a little section in front of the Goals for Texas book that actually explained that stuff.
And nothing that I ever knew had ever gotten to that point of explaining what planning was.
And so I really still tout it as being a very important piece of work.
Leon, as I understand it, that was the result of a compilation of inputs from the regional councils of government.
Yes.
Let me just, for fun, pass around, if y'all will, about half of you.
The goals program that was done, I mentioned the creation of regional councils.
Before we created regional councils,
We created the article 1011M that I mentioned earlier back in 1965.
It said that the state would be divided up by the governor and that there would be regional councils formed in each of the areas.
So if you look, the dark heavy line divides up each of the 24 regions.
And as Bob pointed out, the phase one program was to go out
so to speak, to the people, trying to get out to the folk.
What do you think about it?
What do you think the goals for the state really are?
And they used the regional councils.
By that time, there were 24.
And I remember as a student in the planning school, I went over to Brazos Valley Development Council.
And the governor's staff came down.
And they were talking about the goals program and trying to create goals.
And I sat through some of the committee meetings where they were formulating goals.
And it was kind of a neat experience.
But this program is still one of the highlights of my time.
Let me just mention Bob's book here.
This is one that I didn't bring with me.
Another piece of work that was done during the Preston Smith day was the Urban Development Commission.
At that time, we were really trying to look at
urban problems, urban issues.
We were getting to have a congestion or highway transportation problems.
And Mayor Vandergriff out of Arlington was the the chairman, very impressive guy, very forward thinking guy.
If you look down some of the commissioners, there were really some impressive folks on this.
And it was a
a real credible piece of work.
I don't know if you've ever shown this to them, but this is Bob's copy.
And I think if you'll look at some of the issues that were laid out in this book, this was just remembering this was done in 1970.
So we're 18 years.
But a lot of the issues laid out here, if we had really worked on the issues as we should have and could have, we would have been in much better shape.
Also, Bob had a couple of other things that you can corner him on if you ever need to get into this.
There were some pieces of work, land use planning work done.
Again, this was HUD funded, 701 Housing and Urban Development funded.
Some very forward thinking work done.
This was a piece of work done at the very end of the Connolly administration, talking about model cities, if you look back over
some of the history of urban problems and urban issues, Model Cities was an effort to try to deal with that.
I saw a smile back in the back.
Do you know about Model Cities?
Were you ever involved in it, or no?
He wrote an excellent paper on Model Cities.
On Model Cities?
I don't know how to assess whether it was any good or not.
John Shanahan, that was probably the first student going through this department,
He was working on his Ph.D. when I was here.
I don't know how he was doing that because he was working, too.
I don't know.
He was probably illegal.
Illegal.
But anyway, John Chanahan was up in the governor's office of state-local relations at that time and was working on model cities back in those days.
I still see John.
He's a consultant out of Houston, I believe.
Making megabucks.
He's gone into insurance now.
Oh, is he?
Maybe.
That's why he's making megabucks.
Insuring cellbooks.
I really think those, again, Preston Smith days, great.
Let me try to move into the Doff Briscoe era.
Governor Briscoe was a wealthy landowner, one of the largest single landowners in the state of Texas.
He owns much of South Texas.
So when you saw the land use documents that you were looking at, this was actually done in Preston Smith days.
But some of this work, I don't know if this one was the one or not, but some of this work was actually not distributed until Dolph Briscoe came into office.
And I remember it being held up for four to six months.
And even people commenting on maybe
Had to sue him or something to get this stuff up.
He was not going to literally distribute this land use planning stuff because it was a communist plot kind of stuff.
He really hated land use planning.
The whole concept and thought of any kind of regulation on landowners or limitation of what one can do.
Yeah, I had trouble getting these.
for that reason.
He probably really wouldn't want to give you one.
No, particularly.

But, you know, in your career of planning, it's a little philosophical, but wherever you wind up, be it a city, county, or state, or federal government, you'll find at times you've got to do something, even if you're in an office that's not willing to do something.
I found through my career that there are times when I was hell-bent on getting something done, and the governor just didn't think it was the right thing to do.
As a staff, sometimes your integrity and other things just tell you you've got to do something.
This piece of work was done in 1978.
Even though Doc Briscoe hated land use planning, we were able to get this document out.
We continued to tell him it was no big deal.
a very limited effort, no problems, and we wound up, we didn't give you that one either.
This is a document, though, that I still think, by 78, is a fairly credible piece of work in terms of just trying to recap where the state was at that time and trying to make some projections.
Doc Briscoe, let me just try to say a little bit more about Doc.
I think the only thing that I can say really strong about Doc

was that he did allow us to do the interagency planning council thing that I mentioned earlier, where you have like the Parks and Wildlife Department, agency head, water resources, air control board, all of those state agencies sitting around the table like we are here talking about what our problems are.
Briscoe allowed that to happen.
Briscoe was not one of the take charge kind of governors, so he's not
the type guy that would sit with those agency heads.
But we wound up having a planning director that felt confident enough to do that and demand certain things.
So James M. Rose was the planning director for the first three years.
And he was an extremely confident type guy.
And I found out later on that he used a lot of the governor's name.
to get things done that the governor never would have actually let us do.
Was he from Corpus Christi?
No, he's from Austin.
From Austin.
From the Austin area.
Let me just say that back in 1976, I mentioned the planning and budget struggle.
After James M. Rose left us to go be the water czar for the state of Texas,
Dickie Travis became the director of our combined budget and planning office.
Again, we were all struggling over how to deal with the budget functions and the planning functions.
So we said, OK, we'll solve this.
We'll just combine them.
Seemed like a good idea at the time.
But I'm here to tell you, I don't know if you'll ever have an opportunity to deal with that in your career.
But any time you've got the budget and planning functions combined, I guarantee you the budget's going to outweigh, overpower.
And again, if you had just the right kind of director and leadership, you could make it work.
But it's been my experience that the importance, the continued prodding about budget work, when you're having budget and planning people work at either
What we were trying to do is merge where the expert on transportation was the policy planner and was also the budget analyst for the governor's office.
And it was just very difficult for that kind of thing to happen.
Philosophically, it should.
It should be able to work.
But I never found it to work very well.
Bill Clements came into office in 79.
He was the first Republican in 100 years since Reconstruction.
Everybody was surprised.

Old John Hill was, most of you are not Texas, you don't know about these things, but John Hill was the Democratic nominee and was already over with the rulers, sizing up the office spaces and begun trying to figure out where the pictures should be hung.
And here old Bill Clements came up and won.

It took us for at least six months to try to get our bearings, because there really weren't that many Republicans in Texas, and there weren't that many Republicans that would do governor's office kind of work.
$20,000 to $30,000 a year when most of the Republicans were millionaires.
It just didn't work.
So we all were struggling around trying to figure out how to get the job done.
A guy named Paul Rotenberry, who had been an IBM executive, became our budget and planning director.
And his main claim to fame was MBO, management by objectives,
and implementing all kinds of management kinds of techniques.

This was kind of a new thing to me because when I started thinking about planning, my education here was a process where you gather facts and analyze them, synthesize them, come up with goals and objectives.
Really using management by objectives, it's really a planning process.
It was, you know, developing objectives, trying to lay out where you're going to be by certain times.
So that all of that seemed to be very interrelated.
I really think that, you know, if you look at anything that the Clements first term did, it was to try to reshape government to actually begin thinking about where they're going.
I think that would be a little
checkoff mark I would give Clements for his first term.
His other major piece was a Texas 2000 commission that was another blue ribbon kind of a commission similar to the Urban Development Commission I mentioned earlier.
It was a forward-thinking commission focused primarily on the economic of the future, trying to
project the population, the future budget revenue pictures, and how they merge.
It was at that time in the, oh, about 80, along 80 and 81 was our first major time of struggling over the oil revenue dropping dramatically.
So we wound up really having a struggle with what we're going to do in the future.
Were consultants used by the state government on that?
Consultants?
This was staffed by Clement's type deal, where his whole deal is a public-private partnership stuff where you steal staff.
This staff was, you know, the director was named Vic Arnold of this particular commission.
He was stolen from the University of Texas.
They had to loan him.
He was a great, he was a good guy.
He had been from
one of the northern states, had been a planning director.
But he was staff director for this.
And then we stole about six or eight key staff out of state government, some of the real top people.
And that's uncharacteristic.
But by robbing, stealing, and conniving, we were able to produce.
This was one report, and they produced another one about twice as thick.
on more detailed information about the Texas 2000.
Again, they started, you know, strategic planning seemed to be a term talked about during these days.
Vic was real big on strategic planning.
Not comprehensive planning, but strategic planning.
Because oftentimes you have to really struggle over what folks really mean by those terms.
Let me talk.
briefly about Mark White.
I was talking to Bob before I came in here, and I've got sour grapes a little bit over this, but I'll share it with you.
Mark White had the image.
He was a young, for terms of our governors, he's a young guy, progressive.
He wound up hiring the planning director was Ed Grisham, who
or really that's not his title, but something close to that, who had been the director back in the Preston Smith days.
So I knew that Ed knew how to shake and move and get things done.
So Hardin Wiedemann came, who was a business-type man out of Dallas.
But he was like a Harvard graduate, very sharp guy.
A lot of expectations were raised.
I thought, man, we're going to get some good stuff done.

And really we found, as the administration wore on, that Mark White was not supportive of planning, that the initial things that occurred were just, you know, he was taking advice early on to hire this Ed Grisham, and he was not comfortable with it.
Within six months, they completely reorganized, and anything with the title planning was just kind of shoved aside, and it was strictly, quote, I don't want to plan, I just want to get things done.
and I think was a demise of that particular governor.
Just a lot of neat things that we could have done with a little foresight and then into the action.
Bill Clements beat him.
Very close election.
But again, I think a lot of it was because Mark White
didn't have the management skills to really run an office.
Again, that goes back to being able to pick good people and get the heck out of the way and be at the right place at the right time in terms of providing the leadership.
I'm speaking like a staff guy, but that's the way I feel about it.
Probably has something to do with the campaign, if I may say.
Campaign and true, and it never ended really.
Lack of research.
Yeah, yeah.
Let me just say, Bill Clements, let me talk briefly about that and then move into the sort of the current initiatives, which really picks up what Clements is doing now.
Bill Clements came in this time and, again, put a former legislator, Bob Davis, over the budget planning shop.
And I think, you know, I thought over time I felt like budget has always overpowered planning.
By the time Bob Davis came and organized it, I thought they were going to drop planning out of the name.
But they decided to leave it.
And there was just not much planning done.
I transferred to a new office in the governor's office called the Governor's Office of State Affairs.
It's about a six to seven person policy staff.
And it's been a real experience for me over the last,
You know, it's been a period of completely erasing a lot of the stuff that I had done.
I've been involved with federal grants, been involved with regional council and regional planning for years.
All of that stuff now is still up in budget planning.
But I'm down in a policy development staff now, which is completely a different kind of shop.
And I can talk about it more if you're interested.
But...
Bob Davis completely erased planning.
It's strictly a budget staff up there.
And I'm hopeful that things will change.
Bob Davis just resigned this last week.
And I'm hopeful that a new director might provide a little innovation and a new shape there.
Are you recruiting?
Well, are you interested?
Bob.
Bob would not be accepted in a Republican administration.
You can take that, too.

Let me talk with you now about the Department of Commerce, because I think if you had to be fair about the Clements administration now, I don't think the planning is really coming out of the budget and planning shop.
I think our policies development staff is really more of a planning shop than the budget planning shop.
But I'd have to point to the new Department of Commerce.
This was a brainchild of Bill Clements.
In his previous administration, he decided that we needed to gather together all the economic development kinds of functions in state government and merge them under one agency.
The tourist industry shot it out of the water because the tourist development has a real strong lobbyist group all over the state.
Tourism tends to be a publicity type folk.
And so they can really mobilize their anti-program.
And so it didn't work last term, but Bill Clements this time
decided he was going to do it.
They got Gib Lewis, the speaker, to support him and Hobby.
And so they finally passed a piece of legislation this last session creating this new Department of Commerce.
What's interesting about this whole shop, I mean, you've got the finance over here.
That's the Community Development Block Grant.
As you can tell, some of it's kind of faded out.
But you've got a lot of the Job Training Partnership Act under here, tourism, business development,
But up in the right hand upper corner, research and planning, they actually have a planning shop, a research and planning shop.
And we'll talk a little bit more about that.
But this office is a brand new office.
We have a lot of one of those deals and a lot of expectations.
We hope that a lot of good things will come from this.
Now they've got considerable more financing than we've ever had before.
And we feel like this is going to be a real positive move for us.
Who did you say the executive director was?
This one?
Bill Lauterbach, who is a longtime friend of Clements.
And the original idea of the head of that agency was supposed to be a corporate exec.
but they were looking at a salary of about $70,000, and any kind of low-level corporate exec would be looking at a minimum of $150,000.
So it's really difficult.
You know how professors and corporate execs, about $150,000.
But let me talk about this Strategic Economic Policy Commission.

And I think in terms of planning the next three years, we're going to really need, as students, I'm sure you're not going to be around in the next three years, but whatever job you wind up landing in, you'll need to be watching this commission because I really think this is the grandson of the Texas 2000 Commission.
That's what everybody said.
What happened to the Texas 2000 Commission?
We've got to have somebody looking ahead.
planning for the future.
Believe it or not, the legislation finally called on this commission to be formed.
The governor is chairman.
The lieutenant governor and speaker are on that commission.
The governor's appointees are on there, as well as page two.
There's an agenda that got stuck in the middle here.
But on page two, you'll show appointees.
You'll see the speaker and lieutenant governor has appointees.
So it's a broad-based kind of a group.
It's a bipartisan group.
Hopefully, we'll keep the politics out of it.
It will never happen.
I mean, politics are in everything.
But this is a very bipartisan group.
This little packet, I won't...
Won't belabor you with it, but it does lay out the mission of the commission, the mandates.

It lays out sort of a general schedule of activities, kind of the paper flow process, shows how they plan to get their work done, scheduling public hearings in that, believe it or not, in that process.
So it's something that you just need to look through.
It may be of interest to you in some of your projects.
I have high hopes that this group may be our real key for this next couple of years.
In talking about state planning, just got to say that the way we're structured in Texas, we have over 300 state agencies.
just no way that we could ever have a centralized planning function where, be it the governor or be it another single state agency, to do all the planning for all the agencies.
So philosophically, if we can structure a planning function within each state government, develop it to the best possible planning function that we can do, and then there is a link-up
of all that planning function where everybody knows what's going on and that those planning activities are cast in kind of a complete package.
All the little functional single agency plans need to somehow be drawn together, sort of like the goals for Texas.
That's what the phase two was.
It was each state agency contributed to a overall package.
But we still need the individual agency planning efforts.
Each of our, this is the second to last point, each state agency, somewhere hidden down in the bowels of their state laws, it says that they're supposed to do some kind of planning activity.
It's not emphasized, and as I told Bob coming in here, there are a lot of laws on the books that aren't implemented.
So each of the agencies do
do have individual little silent laws down in their statutory base.
This old piece of work in 73 would point out all those little secret laws.
But it probably needs to be updated since it's probably 13 years old.
Bob, that might be a good project for you.
No comment.
OK, now the last thing that I want to just throw at you, and then I want to hear from you.
A major part of the planning work that's done, probably fairly sketchy but still done, is the use of task forces.
And I don't know.
I mean, this is not my recap of those.
But there are a number of them that Governor Clements has formed through executive order.
And then the legislature directed that certain committees, task forces be formed.
So you'll follow as you flip through.
You've got to be really innovative to be able to read this.
It's stapled in the wrong corner.
But we've got a hog of a machine that staples it where it wants to staple it.
And that's it.
So you take it or leave it.
But you'll flip.
through, you can see everything from kind of an accounting.
The top one we had was it was accounting auditing, financial group trying to every state agency has a different accounting system and a different procedure of keeping track of their expenditure.
They do have to fit a mold a little bit of the comptroller.
But if you'll look at the
Yes.
His Maggie.
I wanted to point out that under water resources, there's no chairman, but they do have staff.
And Ralph Baker was my graduate assistant when he was in the department here.
Ralph is now in budget planning and is on a number of these task forces, as you flip through here.
And would be a good contact on natural resource issues.
He was hired away from the water.
Resources Department.
From Cthulhu.
Cthulhu.
Country boy.
But... Jay Stanford, I see, is chairman of State Emergency Communications.
Yeah, Jay Stanford is the director of the Texas Advisory Commission on Intergovernmental Relations.
